For people who love history, I recommend a guided tour of the Brooklyn Bridge.  I did that last year, and the tour guide was excellent.     Learning of the history behind the Brooklyn Bridge from what it was like before it was built and all the suffering that went into building it made the experience of walk so meaningful to me.     The tour company was Inside-Out.

If I'd expand this list, I would add:
1. Go for a helicopter ride. Yes, it costs, but you won't regret it.
2. Go for a cruise on a sailing boat. Some of them even have live music!
3. Visit Bay Ridge in Brooklyn. By far my favourite neighbourhood, simply stunning!
4. Go to Coney Island. The beach is amazing(I'm from Greece so I have high standards on beaches), and there's also NY aquarium nearby, as well as a luna park and nice spots for food and drink.
5. Visit NY Library. Really beautiful and FREE!
6. Visit National Museum of American Indian. Really nice museum with a few cool activities, also free!!!
7. If you're into sports, madison square garden is a must see!
8. Roam around Washington Heights. Really cool neighbourhood that also has the sylvan terrace, which is simply amazing.


But please people don't stick to only such lists, just go out and explore the city!

Instead of top of the rock which costs a lot of money, you should get a drink at the William Vale Hotel in Brooklyn. The bar is set at the top of the hotel on the 22nd floor. Views are incredible and it's a way more affordable option.

I've lived in New York for 3/4 of a century. Never been to the Lady in the harbor, the Empire state bldg., nor was I ever foolish enough to tour Central Park (Did go through it in a  horse and buggy, about 50 years ago.) You can go to the stables and rent a horse in Manhattan and ride it on legal horse paths. You can go to the Cloisters or grant's tomb and say thanks to him - few people ever go. Go to Riverdale in the Bronx or the BAM in Brooklyn - Coney island. If you have a spare few hundred dollars, sure, go to a broadway play once in your life. I did that back in 1955. Haven't been back. Parking alone is $50, Tickets are hundreds and hundreds and if you want to have dinner you'll pay a fortune for bad food. What he says about the village is true, wander around there check out the layout and the people and the architecture. Ask somebody where the MEWS are - these are hidden, very secret streets and people LIVE there. Stay a week just to see the museums - I used to go every weekend in the 1940's and 50's. Have a steak at the Old Homestead on 13th street. and go to Katz's deli  on Houston street for a once in a lifetime dining experience. Yeah, do Times Square at night. But if you want the skinny, go at 8 a.m. on a Sunday. Never set foot on Staten Island. I never did.

Here are 10 more New York City great Dos in addition to John's great recommendations:
1. To see celebrities in person go to the corner of 53 street and Broadway in Manhattan and go north a few feet up 53 street around 4:30 pm Monday to Fridays (only when the Stephen Colbert Show is taping because sometimes the show is on vacation or is off for a day) and stand behind police barricades that will be there. Then, you'll see the celebrities coming in between 5pm and 6pm across the street from where you'll be standing. Then, when the celebrities finish being on the show they will come out of that side entrance to leave. Many celebs when they are leaving (not when they first arrive) will walk up to the fans and take selfies and shake hands with you. The celebs will walk up to you between 6pm and 45 minutes after that. But, you have to be there early before the fans area fills up.

2. You can also see celebrity guests going to The Jimmy Fallon Show and Seth Meyer Show and if you're lucky Saturday Night Live Show inside 30 Rockerfeller Center (yes that's the same building that the TV show 30 Rock is based on with Tina Fey). That is near the corner of 50 Street and Avenue Of The Americas and try to be there around 5pm inside the lobby and just ask someone which is the elevator to go to The Jimmy Fallon Show. Then just stand in that elevator side where there is a guard that will not let you in that the elevator side. But, you can stand just outside the elevator side.

3. If you want to see a specific celebrity that is staring in a Broadway stage show, go to that theater early (especially on weekdays) and ask one of the theater employees where is the side entrance (not the main entrance) where the celebrities come in through and at what time do they arrive which can vary since some celebs come in hours before to put on make-up or costumes for the show. Others don't.

4. If you are a fan of basball (The Yankees, The Mets), you can find out when they are in town playing in their stadium and get tickets for The Yankees (in The Bronx) taking the 4 train to 161 Street or for The Mets to the stop called Citi Field on the 7 train. This way you can see some of the most famous athletes.

5. If you want to see a free live music concert from the top singers in the world, during the summer NBC TV network has free concerts near the ice rink in a court yard area in between buildings away from traffic in Rockefeller Center. These shows are presented by The Today Show in the morning during weekdays. Check listings to see when and who will be performing.

6. If you want to see celebrities being interviewed check 92 Y celebrity interviews on YouTube to get an idea of how that place is and call that place by Googling it to find out the upcoming schedule of future celebrity interviews.

7. If you are a Seinfeld fan, there is a Seinfeld bus tour that will take you to the famous real places mentioned on the Seinfeld Show. Google it.

8. If you want to go to the actual dive bar where Lady Gaga hangs out (and used to perform at before she became famous) go to 123 Rivingston Street in The Lower East Side of Manhattan. Google Map it.

9. If you are a fan of old Jazz and of Louis Armstrong, just Google Louis Armstrong house museum which is in Queens, New York across the river from Manhattan to actually walk around Louis house inside and see and touch his furniture which is still there the way he left it when he died.

10. If you want to visit the graves of some of the most famous celebrities in the history of this planet, just search on YouTube famous celebrity graves in New York City and look at those videos and pick which celebrity graves you want to see and just Google Map each individual cemetery that has those graves. Google at what time each cemetery opens and closes and go early to spend a quiet peaceful day walking around those iconic tomb stones.

I hope my recommendations helped some of you. Remember to stay away from expensive overpriced places. Some of the best food in NYC are in ethnic neighborhoods like China Town in Manhattan, Little Italy on Mulberry street, the Latin Neighborhood of Washington Heights in Manhattan, the Russian neighborhood of Brighton Beach in Brooklyn and some hot spots like Ethiopian Food, Indian Food, Thai Food, and Philippines Food areas throughout the city. Cheers.

Ok everyone my man did a good job but he might not have some of the native knowledge you need to know. First and foremost, his pizza recommendations are totally wrong and tourists traps. Johns on bleeker, joes on 7th. Avoid dollar slices they‚Äôre great on a budget but you‚Äôre visiting, get the good stuff. In Brooklyn Difaras is best all NYC but its deep in Brooklyn, otherwise Lucalis is amazing in iconic neighborhood of carrol gardens Brooklyn. Brooklyn. You must spend at least 2 days in Brooklyn alone there‚Äôs just as much to do as in the city (Manhattan). You‚Äôre gonna want to see iconic Coney Island and get your Nathans hot dog, if you‚Äôre visiting during the summer you simply can‚Äôt pass on Coney Island. South Brooklyn (near Brooklyn bridge) is amazing and has some of the best restaurants in NY. If in season go to the Bronx for a Yankees game then arthur avenue after for dinner thats the real little Italy.
Here‚Äôs the real pro tips:
1. Walk fast on busy streets or you‚Äôll see why we have a reputation (thats not true at all) for being rude, if you‚Äôre walking slow your actually the one being rude.
2. This ONLY applies in busy areas during the rush. Don‚Äôt make eye contact or smile at strangers, especially on the subway. Again this is rude.
3. If in a busy deli/store/pizzeria no small talk, the words please and thank you are meaningless. Give your order, get out the way, have your payment ready. Holding up the flow is again rude, and the cashier probably deals with thousands of people a day, they just cant give everyone attention.
4. Avoid staten island, its a dump (no really it is) and the people there are terrible.

Basically go by the old saying ‚Äúwhen in rome, do as the romans do‚Äù NYC is Rome.
Don‚Äôt be nervous, believe me we‚Äôre some of the friendliest people in the world despite what you heard. You need directions ask somebody (just not someone walking fast with their head down) you‚Äôll get them, detailed with patience, and probably followed by a recommendation. Our night life is unmatched, make friends but don‚Äôt trust anyone if thats makes sense. Until you actually get to know them. It‚Äôs not that we‚Äôre untrustworthy it‚Äôs just that there are a lot of scams.
Remember its a city of 8.5 million people and has as many as 15 even 20 million on a given day with commuters and tourists. Some are gonna be jerkoffs, but most are cool. We‚Äôre a city made up of every walk of life, and we pretty much all get along. We wouldn‚Äôt have it any other way. In NYC it doesn‚Äôt matter where you‚Äôre from/ what you believe, its how you act.
Follow my advice and the videos you‚Äôll have the time of your life! After all, it‚Äôs the greatest city in the world.

1 dont wave your wallet in the air especially when you see a guy racing towards you in a bike, i have seen people have their wallets taken right of of their hands in broad daylight. or they will steal it out of your back pocket

11 in the summer watch for air conditioners and fans falling from apartment windows

The best thing about NY imo is the shows! I saw Kinky Boots, Aladdin and the NYC Ballet (highly recommend). I liked the Rockefeller Centre for the views both during the day and at night. For shops Macys Herald Square is the best department store (I went to them all). I did a photography tour which was great and got some awesome shots of Grand Central, NY public library and Times Square. I was so bored at the museums compared to Paris'. Dont go over the Brooklyn Bridge on the weekend - it was the first sunny day all week and was like being a zombie herd. I stayed for about 2 weeks and was eager to move on so would recommend about only 5 days.

I stayed at the Renaissance Times Square which is a wonderful hotel and the bar directly overlooks the red stairs/screens so we got a great view without going outside. Very noisy and if I was to go again I would probably stay around Herald Square as it is still mid town but near great restaurants.

I went to all 4 observation decks and I have to say "Top of the Rock" is the best for views, since there are no glass windows in the upper deck. Second is the Empire State Building, mostly because it's so iconic, it has great views at nighttime too, the fence is a bit in the way for photos. Only then would come One World Trade Center, it's definitely the cleanest, and in general good for photos during bad weather, but has no outdoor area. The worst was "The Edge", I would only go there early in the morning, since people lean on the glass, and it gets dirty quickly, making it hard to take good pictures. Go in the night or morning to avoid the crowds.

My favorite things to do in NYC
1) Go to Central Park and explore the wooded areas, take a nap on the lawn or rent a canoe/bicycle.
2) Food. There is so much good food. I enjoy the pizza, tacos, Halal, Chinese, Italian etc..
3) Coney Island. Takes around 1 hour to get to Coney Island beach via the subway from Manhattan. I like to just relax, feel the sun and breeze and listen to the waves crash.
4) Staten Island Ferry. Free Ferry that travels between lower Manhattan and Staten Island with great views of the city and statue of liberty, going at night time is the best.
5) Governor's Island. You can take a ferry here from the same terminal as Staten Island Ferry. This is a small getaway island just south of Manhattan with parks, fields, playgrounds, trails, views, hammocks and more.
6) Visit Times Square at night
7) Walk down 5th ave and see all the fancy stores/shopping

As someone who lives in NYC, I'll tell you all the facts. Chinatown is a good place to go to, but is usually crowded and most restaurants are super small due to limited space. Unless you want to get a good meal or taste of the asian culture there, then there's really no point in going. Some museums such as the Natural History Museum, are VERY crowded and by that, I mean you can't barely walk through the entrance. Don't even mention the lines- buy your tickets as early as possible! On a summer weekend, the line usually measures up to two blocks. I highly recommend Time Square. It's a huge tourist attraction anyway, and it is the PERFECT place to see a broadway show! script of the video, you're welcome :

New York is situated in the Northeast region of the United States of America.
Over eight million call the Big Apple home, and the city attracts up to fifty million visitors a year.

Ever since the Colonists arrived in 1624, New York has been continuously shaped by the waves of immigrants drawn here by the promise of hope, and liberty.
Every newcomer arrived with a cultural suitcase that contributed to the sounds, tastes and textures of New York.
But it is their dreams which built the city. A city like no other!

New York touches not only the heavens with its mystic skyline, its influence radiates to every corner of the globe. Every street it seems, is familiar through documentary, movie and song.
New York straightforward grid system makes it an easy city to explore by foot, taxi, or its subway, which just like the city, never sleeps!

In Manhattan‚Äôs Midtown, you‚Äôll find many of The Big Apple‚Äôs most iconic symbols.
The Art Deco-designed Empire State Building is one of the most impressive and endearing skyscrapers ever created.
The skyline may have grown up around it, but the view from the 102nd floor is as breathtaking today as it was when it first opened in 1931.

New York has always been a place where ‚Äúwhen the going got tough, the tough got going‚Äù.
The Rockefeller Center, a visionary city within a city, rose during the darkest days of the Great Depression. Today, it‚Äôs still a place of creativity, inspiration and even more incredible views of the city.

Closer to earth is Grand Central Terminal. Step in the Main Concourse, and feel the echo of every tearful farewell and joyous greeting throughout the station‚Äôs history.

New York has always been the gateway to the Land of the Free, but it is also the city of the spree, the shopping spree! This city is shopaholic heaven, and Fifth Avenue with the eye-popping window displays is the high temple of the retail world.

Times Square, one of the most visited tourist attractions on the planet. Stand here on the corner of Broadway and Seventh Avenue, and you stand at the crossroads of the world. It‚Äôs also a place to snap up a half-price ticket to a Broadway show.

New York has been blessed with generous civic spaces. But there is no greater chill-out space in the Big Apple than Central Park, a beautiful 850-acre network of meadows and lakes. This is the place where New Yorkers come to rest, romance, and express themselves.

Over the decades many New Yorkers made it big, and much of that fabulous wealth was reinvested into collecting some of the greatest artworks on the planet. Nowadays, much of this art is available for everyone to enjoy. A walk through The Metropolitan Museum of Art is a walk through 5000 years of humankind‚Äôs greatest creative moments.

The Frank Lloyd Wright designed-Guggenheim is a different kind of walk, one which spirals ever-upward through a dizzying collection of 20th and 21st Century masterpieces.

Newcomers to NY spend much of their time looking skyward, but since the 2001 attacks on the World Trade Center, a new attraction gives locals and visitors a chance to pause and bow their heads. The Reflecting Absence memorial and museum honors the 3000 people who lost their lives on that darkest of September days.
New York resonates with the sounds of over 800 language groups, and nothing epitomizes this diversity like the city‚Äôs neighborhoods. Little Italy packs all the tastes and flavors of Italy into just a couple of streets, while Soho attracts cool cats and well-heeled bohemians form all over the world.
A few streets away, Greenwich Village proudly retains the caf√©s and bars where creative residents like Bob Dylan first performed before becoming American icons. And then there are the boroughs.
Walk across the Brooklyn Bridge to the melting pot of Brooklyn. With its own distinctive neighborhoods, museums, open spaces, and who could forget Coney Island!
So welcome to New York City, The Big Apple. We‚Äôve only just given you a bite-sized taste of what this incredible city has to offer. But if you‚Äôve got an appetite for the very best things that life has to offer, this is the destination for you there‚Äôs enough to feast on here for a lifetime!

HERE IS HOW TO BE LIKE A NEW YORKER
¬†-Don't wear I LOVE NY SHIRTS.
-Where comfortable and fashionable clothes that you would usually wear.
-Don't stare at people.
-Don't walk with an electrical device out.
-use the crosswalk on red lights (it saves time and its really not that dangerous)
-Ignore the homeless people. They are just gonna use the money they have to get some of DAT booze!
-Buy food from street vendors. The food is actually really good.
-Don't hesitate or stop on the middle of the sidewalk
-Know how to hail a cab. step off the curb and put your hand up.
-Buy some cheap stuff from Chinatown.
-NEVER EVER EVER use underground/indoor parking lots. THEY COST A FORTUNE and you could just find a regular parking spaces for FREE!
-Be aggressive when looking for a parking space.
-Never use buses. They are slow(they stop every block and often get stuck in traffic).
-Know where you are going.
-Don't just stand in the middle of Times Square.
-Be patient when in a traffic jam. (AT least its better than LA! Holy shit that is pure hell!)
-Take the subway if possible.
-Take off you're sweater/jacket in the subway (its underground and really hot).
-Don't complain about high prices of food and tip nicely.
-Avoid nasty neighborhoods (AKA the BRONX! okay im bein kinda racist but theres a lot of blacks there).
-Lock your car and hide valuables.
-Walk quickly and go with the flow.
-and lastly... ENJOY YOUR STAY

THESE ARE MY TIPS FROM A NEW YORKER (ME) BORN AND RAISED IN THE BIG CITY!

Great video! I would say that sometimes you do need to have some extra cash on hand for tips, bodegas, buskers, ice cream/hot dogs in Central Park, street vendors etc. Some places only take cash. Also, about hotels - if you are planning to do sightseeing mostly in Manhattan, I would rather pony up the extra money to stay in Manhattan and be able to walk, explore and be closer to the sights I want to see on my time instead of staying somewhere in the outer boroughs just for the cheaper hotel ...you can have the best intentions about taking trains wherever you need to go during the day and at night, but if you happen to have a few late nights out, safety can be a concern and if you're not quite sure about taking the subway, you will be taking cabs/Lyfts/Ubers back to your hotel in the outer boroughs and that cost can add up (and take up time, too).

When it comes to weather and what to wear‚Ä¶..I‚Äôm sure it‚Äôs just the tri-state area that experiences this but specifically here in NY‚Ä¶.the weather is bipolar and sometimes disrespectful.

Just come back from there. New York was somewhat disappointing, talking about the city itself. It was lovely to be away for a few days and we enjoyed it but we found New York itself has gone downhill certainly since we were last there in 2011. It‚Äôs super expensive now, on a par with central London prices, if not more! And when you add on the required tip for practically everything it really adds up. The tip culture is something I don‚Äôt care for, because it‚Äôs expected at not at the discretion of the paying customer. Even if you leave what they deem to be the wrong amounts of tip in other words not enough, they make that known in no uncertain terms! Not nice. Minimum tip they expect is 20%, and up to 30% in some instances. That sort of extra on top of already inflated prices, not helped by the poor exchange rate makes it extremely expensive.
We also found the streets very dirty and marijuana has now been legalised so every street corner stinks of the stuff! Not pleasant.
The subway is an experience in itself, full of deranged weirdos. A lot of very threatening and intimidating people on the platforms and trains i have to say. I never feel frightened on the London Underground but I did in NYC. I‚Äôm afraid New York has gone back to where it was in the 1980s in my view.
I‚Äôve painted a very bleak picture but that said we still nonetheless had a nice time and enjoyed some wonderful food and got to see a play and did a little shopping etc so we‚Äôre still glad we went but shan‚Äôt be rushing back anytime soon. Will try other US cities in future.

I live in lower Manhattan and have a toddler side kick. The Staten Island Ferry is a wonderful place where we go to burn off her little kid energy. It is a safe and scenic boot ride. You can move around the entire trip. You"re allowed to eat and drink. I like the back of the boat, so I wait for everyone to board, my granddaughter and I wave at the workers on the boat and ramp, go right up stairs or go forward and take the elevator up, if we have a stroller. The back of the boat is emptier and the view is amazing. I like the view to the east, Governor's Island and Brooklyn. The Statue of Liberty and the tourists are on the west side of the boat.
The Staten Island Zoo is an easy car service ride away. It is a good small zoo for little children. The mall on the Staten Island side is a good place for children because it is mostly empty. It was empty when we were there last summer.
It's not for adult tourists as much as it is for locals or people who are here for a long time. I have only gone at mid day during the week.

1. Dont go to hotels unless you wanna be hella fancy or you hella rich, go stay at a Airbnb as she said, it's more affordable
2. I get you want to do some restauraunts and all that, yes do that, dont forget that there are some delis or bodega as we say that have good sandwiches, I recommend the chopped cheese on a roll.
3. There's free entertainment everywhere, just gotta know where to look, free movies in the park, free shows/concerts. Broadway is good but tickets can be expensive if you dont look up todaytix.
4. Explore the outer borough, there's more than just manhattan you know, even Staten Island...ONCE. The bronx got some culture, Queens got the foods, Brooklyn got the yuppies gentrifyers but more importantly it got history.
5. Learn our subway system map and you wont get lost...much
6. Get out of the way, we got places to go and things to do, we friendly but dont mess with our gait.
7. As she said, dress comfortably, look at the weather before you go and use your best judgement.
8. Good Luck

Manhattan is great in the Fall but in many ways is better in the summer. For example, Central Park is much nicer in the summer than in the fall/winter imo.  That's because more people are there hanging out in the summer and people are more relaxed/the vibes are better (rather than people racing to get out of the chilly weather).   Plus the trees, shrubs are nicer in the summer.  Times Square also I would say is better in the summer because it is not cold and people are more willing to relax and hang out.  Also, the Charging Bull statue is literally right next to Battery Park which IS beautiful in the Fall and has great views of the Statue of Liberty.  Also, Rockefeller Center is iconic so I don't think it was a bad choice but if you have more time, Bryant Park and Union Square Park are also really great in the late fall/winter.

You‚Äôre doing NYC wrong well most of it. Day 1 should be the Met (they don‚Äôt allow filming), Central Park with the the balto statue (the dog who saved billions during a massive illness outbreak in Alaska), try to find a greys papaya for lunch as it‚Äôs decent dogs, Empire State Building for sunset, finally Korea town for Korean bbq, desserts I would go to serendipity. Day 2 start with breakfast at a bagel place with a smear and some smoked salmon, go to the Statue of Liberty with Ellis island, head back to Chinatown for lunch (I pick nom wah tea house for dim sum), explore Chinatown a bit with little Italy next block, head to Chelsea for the art scene, eat a entire pizza at Lombardi‚Äôs for dinner, finally head to times square to explore at night and enjoy the three minute art displays near midnight on the screens. Day 3 try to find a diner nearby and eat a decent breakfast, head to DUMBO or Coney Island for a bit of exploring, go down to Wall Street to admire the stock exchange, go to Eataly by Madison square park as it‚Äôs a giant food hall for a good lunch, try shopping at Macy‚Äôs or try to find stores you like, for dinner try little Italy as most of the area is quite good. Day four try a foreign breakfast like Chinatown or something, try the Empire State Building or World Trade Center for the views, for lunch try 99 favors hotpot.

Native New Yorker here. Fun video as always but it breaks my heart a little. You guys visited zero of the black/latino/asian neighborhoods. People in our generation all grew up listening to at least some hip-hop, yet most of us rather go see the "Friends" building than go to see the literal birthplace of hip-hop.

If you want to citibike through central park, take the subway up to 125th street (Harlem). Check out some of the food and support the black-owned businesses there, go to East Harlem and check out some of the latino culture there. Then get a citibike and enter Central park through 110th Street and bike down the length of the park. Check out the turtle pond. Go to the "Imagine" memorial and hear the buskers playing beatles songs. Check out the Dakota building where John Lennon was shot. Then bike through midtown and go all the way to Chinatown and have some of the food there and take in the sights.

There's a lot more to do but you guys only had a few days.

As a native New Yorker, I'm always curious what you tell first time visitors. One tip on hailing a cab, do NOT step out into the street, stand on the edge of the curb and put you hand up. Many people step out into the street and that is dangerous. As for pizza, GREAT suggestion regarding Patsy's in Harlem. Not only is it the ONLY Patsy's location worth visiting, they have several, but the one in Harlem, on 1st Avenue, was an inspiration for the restaurant scene in "The Godfather", check out the men's room, seriously. There's also a terrific little pizza place across the street from the theater that shows "Hamilton". As for Times Square, avoid it. For food, you can find so many wonderful options 2 blocks west on 9th Avenue. Lately I've been eating my way down that street and the choices are endless, though for basic and consistently great food, we stop at Mom's. For another hot dog vendor, there's a guy in front of the Metropolitan museum that is great. He's a veteran and grills his dogs, instead of boiling them. I know, getting long winded here..one last thing. Walking the Brooklyn Bridge. YES! Do it!! But go from Manhattan to Brooklyn, then walk over to the nearby Manhattan Bridge and underneath is an amazing food court with some iconic choices, or walk a few blocks up Flatbush Avenue Extension to the original Juniors, great food and the best cheesecake you'll ever have. Then walk back. Give it a few hours, walking in NYC is the best way to get around!! Be safe!

Nice video. We just got back after our 30th + visit, and one thing I will say is NYC is dynamic.

Yellow Cab ‚Äî yes, from the airport. Way more convenient than Uber because they right there waiting for you. And if you are staying in Manhattan, I say Newark is the best airport. This last visit, we had our bags in ten minutes! We were in Murray Hill in less than an hour from the time or plane reached the gate. Have not tried the new and improved Laguardia yet. JFK is still an absolute nightmare to be avoided at all costs. We take an Uber or car service back to the airport.

Observation deck ‚Äî absolutely. But why not spend the $40 a person and eat at a great restaurant with an amazing view ‚Äî Manhatta in the Wall Street area on the 60th floor with great views. Awesome. Do some sights and then a great lunch or dinner.

Pizza yes! We like Norma Gatronomia Sicilia.

Deli yes! Every visit we must have deli. Our current favorite is 2nd Avenue. And if you are the LES try Russ & Daughters Cafe. Have a board and an egg cream. We happen to like Katz. We order their pastrami by the pound so we always have some on hand.

Dirty water dog? Its been decades. Grew until going to Nathans out the Bronx River Parkway. Used to love Grey‚Äôs Papaya ‚Äî all gone. There is still one Papaya King. I saw that Nathans has carts in front of the MET. One of these days we we take the subway out to Coney Island for Nathans and walk the beach where my dad was a lifeguard back the 40‚Äôs.

Central Park ‚Äî Picnic! Hit the bodega, get some sandwiches and lay out by Turtle Pond, the Great Lawn, or any of a myriad places. Try not to be on the go constantly. Slow down and relax. We were in Manhattan for a week and spent time in a park every day. Our newest ‚Äúdiscovery‚Äù is the gelato shack at Madison Square Park across the street from Eately.

Broadway or off broadway show, jazz club or a comedy club. A fantastic, only in New York experience.

We went through Central Park South and the mid section, but not Central Park North; so I went on my own a month later to explore and discovered two waterfalls in Central Park North.  Who would have thought Manhattan had waterfalls?  Central Park is so massive that it‚Äôs impossible to explore all of it in one day IMO. Just returned from 7 nights in Manhattan NY, first time visitors from Spain. My thoughts..

We walked ‚Äòeverywhere‚Äô on purpose, why ride the subway when you can walk and see the sights? On some days we did 15 miles walking‚Ä¶and we are both in/around our 60s and the arthritis in my knees killed me but I would not change it.

The cost, its Expensive, offensively so, here in Spain a beer at a local bar 2,60$.. NY 7$ for a house beer during happy hour, get the wrong beer at wrong hour.. 14$..

I don‚Äôt smoke, if i did, in Spain 5$ a packet, Manhattan back street store 18$

Meal sizes are 30% larger than we have here, we side stepped this by just eating once a day.

Must visit? Stattin island Ferry, its free, great views of the statue of Liberty.

Ground Zero. Seeing the memorial pools was enough, i had enough flashbacks that the museum tour would have crushed me, i saw the events on tv live on the day, shed enough tears and still carry the scars.

‚ÄòKeens Steakhouse‚Äô.. excellent meal, book in advance, ask for Lincoln room, hell they were able to give me blue cheese and crackers with a glass of Port as dessert (i am old school) but finally tally was 400$+ for two for dinner.

Shopping in Times Square is nuts, no matter what size you are you will find it but again not cheap, 15$ a T shirt no brand here, 180$ in Times Square for T shirts.

Plain Hot Dog 3$

Ride on a horseback carriage? 65$ for 20 minutes. Yellow cab? Quick convenient and expensive, 5,5 mile / 7,5km was 36$.

Points of note. The steam coming up from the streets is famous, makes for some good photos, the smells, the street vendors give the city an amazing bbq/curry smell that just makes you hungry by walking..

Best time to shop? 9am to 12.. after 12 its just to busy.

Biggest disappointment? All the ‚Äòmust eat / must visit‚Äô places are over crowded, went to tacos number 1, faced a 1 hour wait with no seating (chelsea market) and Katz was the same with no hope in hell of a seat.. my advice, go at 4am.. with my arthritis no way i could stand that long.
I‚Äôll be going on the 23rd‚Ä¶ How do you feel about the weather?

Here's a secret that made traversing NYC via train much easier - the subway travels in the direction of traffic! Say you want to go downtown from Times Square, turn towards the direction you want to go and get into the subway station on the right side of the road.

Another one are the ferries. You can get very nice views of Manhattan by taking the ferry north from Pier 6 in Brooklyn Bridge Park. Tickets are just $4.

Regarding OMNY, great system, shame they haven't rolled it out to the AirTrain or LIRR. I would love to see more cooperation between the different transport agencies. One app for the LIRR, another for the ferries, and only MetroCard for AirTrain is a bit too much. Worst of all LIRR app doesn't even work with foreign cards so you have to get the ticket from the machines.

Do tourists really complain about having to walk in nyc? That is actually maddening. The crown jewel of NYC is its walk-ability.

That tip on shoes is spot on. I visited Manhattan in 2018 and my old worn down very loosely fitting sneakers with me. Had at least 6 blisters on each foot by the end of the day. Also if you're not simply used to walking a lot i recommend you literally start taking walks daily 5-6 weeks before your trip. Living extremely sedentary lifestyle and then all of sudden you walk and stay on your feet the whole day will wreck your feet no matter how good of a shoe pair you got.

The Staten Island Ferry is another nice 25 minute cruise between Staten Island and Manhattan (at the base of Battery Park). It runs every 20 minutes during rush hour (6am-9am) and (4pm-8pm). It's every half hour other times. Best of all? You can get great pics of the Statue of Liberty and is free. It runs 24 hours.
As a New Yorker I can definitely say you hit the nail on the head---perfect tips for tourists and actually residents, too!

The ‚Äúpointing at the indication board‚Äù is adapted from Japan rail companies.

They‚Äôre trained to point at indicator signed and vocalize what the sign means. This greatly reduces operational mistakes. In the case of the NYC system it indicates to the conductor that the train is positioned properly on the platform to then open the doors safely as some platforms actually have signals mid-platform which the driver must obey resulting is the train not fully in the station. On the NYC subway, it‚Äôs the conductor, not the driver who controls the doors unlike most other cities with staffed trains.

That's awesome you mentioned the Long Island Railroad. I boarded the railroad instead of the subway accidentally and ended up saving myself 45 mins. I didn't have a ticket when they checked for tickets (I had a Metro Card), but was able to buy a ticket on board to Grand Central for $5.

As a resident of Eastern Queens, I have an added tip for the LIRR from Jamaica to Penn Station from JFK. There is a ticket option called CityTicket that you can ride any off-peak train for $5.00 one way anywhere within Zones 1 and 3(Manhattan Brooklyn and Queens Stations.) It is valid all week on off-peak trains only. I use it all the time going between my home and Manhattan.

Want a beautiful view of the Manhattan skyline and a trip of the harbor for $2.75?

Take the NYC Ferry from E 90th street and East End Ave. The ferry (the BLUE line) makes a stop at 34th street, but stay on the ferry to Wall Street/11th Street. You get spectacular views of FIVE East River bridges and the Financial District skyline.

Then you can transfer FOR FREE to the Rockaway (PURPLE) Line -- it will make a stop at Sunset Park/Brooklyn Army Terminal, but stay on it to the next and last stop, Rockaway.

It gives you a glorious view of Governors Island (another great side trip from South Ferry Manhattan) and you go under the Marine Parkway Bridge. Once you get there, you can walk the boardwalk or do a pub crawl (in summer season), or you can just walk a few blocks from the ferry terminal to the Beach 105th Street A line subway stop to come back to Manhattan (for another $2.75).

Great video, thank you. I'm a fan of your helpful points of view and glad you've made it to my home city. I have a correction: no right on red, ever. In all 5 boroughs (Brooklyn, Queens, Manhattan, the Bronx, and Staten Island) drivers are not allowed to turn right during a red light. (That doesn't mean it's strictly enforced.) And if you're walking all bets are off.

Fellow fans and NYC travelers: Johnny T's NYC Tourist Tips is also a helpful video. The advice in it is spot on from us who live here. Kindly keep out of the way of the steady flow of foot traffic, especially during rush hour.

My recommendations:
Central Park is a must. The corner of East 59th Street & 5th Avenue is one of the best crossroads in the world. It's the horse-and-carriage corner of the park, across the street is the Plaza hotel, catty corner is the Apple Store (the one that is a glass cube). To the north on 5th Avenue, you have Museum Mile with The Metropolitan Museum of Art, The Guggenheim, and many others. To the south on 5th Avenue, you have Tiffany's, St. Patrick's Cathedral, and Rockefeller Center.

Do not rent a car here. First of all, you're going to get killed in rental and parking charges (plus tax). Secondly, the average is 6.5 mph (10.4 km/h) driving in Manhattan. Use your smart phone to get subway directions, or just walk.

Enjoy and Thank you

If you're doing the tourist thing, the Metropolitan Museum of Art is a must see plus you get the additional bonus of a three-day pass to all the museums that are run by the Met such as the Cloisters, which is a particular favorite of mine. Essentially this means one full day at the Met with two more to see the other stuff. Be aware that the price is by suggested donation for New Yorkers and $25 for everyone else, but that's still a great deal since 1) the Met is one of the greatest museums of art in the world (plus you don't have to wait an hour or more to get in for same-day tickets), and 2) you get the other museums in the system as add-on. Also visit the Main Branch of the New York Public Library on 5th Avenue; it's a veritable temple of learning and the architecture is fantastic.

My wife and I are going to NYC in August (our first trip, although I went there so far back (without proper resources) it doesn't really count) and then in September we're going back to Mexico City for a second time, after enjoying a week there over the holidays 2017/2018.  I expect both cities to have pluses and minuses.  We're from the Los Angeles area, so we have that as a lifelong benchmark, both good and bad.  I will be particularly interested in two things, since culture and food are wonderful in both places (and, yes, Californians largely do NOT know what good pizza tastes like):  1.  Convenience of public transportation and 2. Cost-per-benefit ratio.  My own personal experience with public trans (largely the metro/subway system) for Los Angeles is F, for Chicago it's a B, and for CDMX, Buenos Aires and Santiago, Chile it's an A.  Plus, in Mexico City, you can go ANYWHERE for five or six pesos!  That's 25 to 30 cents, USD.  Simple, affordable, and it gets around a city which probably is slightly bigger than NYC.  The other thing is food.  Quality of food is probably equal (as a Californian, I am absolutely DYING to try authentic NY pizza (having a taste for it in Connecticut/Mass./Upstate NY).  But so far, my favorite food in all the world is CDMX genuine street/sidewalk food.  There is no froo-froo involved:  fresh ingredients, purchased at a nearby market, no preservatives, no tricks, no hidden ingredients, all prepared while you watch (and not too long!), friendly neighbors offering a chair or a tip, and a genuine, almost family atmosphere, for ALWAYS less than $5, usually even less.  It's hard to beat, and it's addictive.  Who knew you could do so much with fresh produce and a little fresh chicken, pork or beef?  Still, I am excited by our late-summer visit to NYC and exploring just a few of its highlights (we will have tix to a game at Yankee Stadium), but especially the off-the-beaten track places, like we did in CDMX and Buenos Aires.  We find that back streets are the places where you really discover the culture and the people.  Geez.  I'm long-winded about this.  Sorry.

I guess this video is around a year old so... whoops on my part. But I just have to let people know of bagels with lox since you didn't mention it. If you're at a bagel shop seriously consider it, every shop will have it. It's more substantial than a bagel for breakfast and it's really more of a sandwich. For me it's the best way to get a bagel, hands down.

Lox is salmon, and when served on a bagel should come with cream cheese, capers, and red onion at a minimum. It might sound odd if you haven't had fish dairy and capers in one place, but I promise it's amazing. A quintessential NYC staple.

Do not come to the US and expect not to ever tip the waitstaff, don't be that asshole tourist. Being an American I find tipping to be an outdated method (restaurants should pay them a decent amount. It is silly for them to rely on consumers to pay for their living expenses) but I do not take that out on them by revengefully not tipping when the service is good, if it's bad then don't. We understand a lot of other countries do not do this, but we do.

If you just don't want to tip then don't go to any sit-down meals. (Hell, my husband doesn't like tipping the workers at Sonic so we pull in a carspot, see what we want on the menu then head to the drive thru and order.)

For travelers, about tipping - yes tip 15% on your check (no need to go over 15%) BUT to make you happy here's the good thing --> Be sure to make the servers work twice as hard for that 15% tip. Make yourself feel like a King when you're dining, extra sauce, extra this extra that, refills. (Only as needed but the point is don't hesitate to ask EXTRA Stuff)

Most importantly if you do not like the food brought to you (be it for taste/temperature or whatever) DO NOT hesitate to send it back. Call your server and have them bring you fresh food (say please). Yes make the restaurant work for you because it's your money. Many tourists would just eat whatever even if you they don't like it, Do not do that. You are the King over here, demand good food and service, that's where this tipping culture in America comes in.

1. Do not accept anything that anyone hands you (even if they are just offering their hand to shake yours), especially at tourist spots. More often than not, it's a setup for a scam.

Tip: Avoid Times Sq like the plague! Grab a few pics if you can get through the crowds then leave, there's absolutely nothing there except over-priced chain food restaurants. Although the subway system, the MTA is 24 hours, it gets painfully slow after midnight with many interrupted stops, so if you're a party goer, cab will have to be it. I recommend using a ride sharing service like VIA, it's the most economical I've found at any given time within Manhattan. If you're coming from a cleaner and civilized country, jk, but seriously don't be surprised at how dirty NYC is, the effort to promote recycling is just not really encouraged here and it's a shame. That being said NYC has SO much to offer and that's just the city, if you venture out to Long Island like Montauk after the summer season is simply serene. I live in Queens, born and raised here and it's one of the must culturally diverse places ever! I've traveled all around Europe, South America, Asia and nothing beats the food in NYC. I can't find midnight ramen or roti massaman delivered to my door anywhere else. I live in Flushing, Queens and the food has always been the highlight of living here. If you're feeling adventurous try Hahm Ji Bach for Korean BBQ it's 24hrs it's 30min from Manhattan taking the Long Island Rail Road a few stops from Penn Station, Murray Hill stop.

Major error!!  Cars (vehicles) are generally NOT allowed to turn right in New York City.  The rule applies to NEW YORK STATE (except in cities with more than a million residents, a code which effectively translates to "Except New York City.")  Exceptions to the New York STATE rule (outside of New York City) are marked "NO TURN ON RED," and occur frequently, especially in New York City suburbs.  Exceptions INSIDE New York City are marked "RIGHT ON RED PERMITTED," but such signs are not very common.

America is different so don't judge, you dont think you should tip because you're naive. Ask anyone who has been a waiter, especially as a busy restaurant and they'll give you the exact opposite respone. you feel so robbed of your hard work when customers don't tip. Not every business works as simply as you think. Every restaurant is different and the cost of food sometimes barely covers the expense of making it and then paying all the kitchen staff and enough for the owners to make a profit, otherwise why open a restaurant. The servers on the other hand are the most expendable parts of a restaurant business and get paid something like $2 an hour. And some restaurants, waiters dont get a wage so if you tip nothing, they literally go home to their families with nothing. so imagine you working for 10 hours and everybody tipped nothing. you would make $20 for a whole day's work, enough to pay for your gas going to and from work sometimes.. 15% of $60 is $9 + $2.50 wages from the business = $11.50... Now compare this with the minimum wage paid by most London eateries - $10.15. Now considering both are likely to be serving multiple tables/patrons each hour (e.g. 15% of $60 *4 = $36/H!!!), the NYC waiter/waitress stands to make a considerable amount more then their London counterparts as British norms do not call for tipping (Hence per hour rate of $10.50). All in all, I think the waiting staff do alright... Tip if the service was good, if not don't tip at all.

Two things about NYC that one needs to factor in (and I say this living an hour away)- Wind and going in and out. The gust of wind that is a mild factor in, say, Brooklyn, might not be felt by the wall of buildings in Manhattan- BUT  then you turn a corner into a wind tunnel. Likewise, what's a good outfit for walking in the cold might be a bad outfit once you're inside. So, say, if your Day is to go to one cafe for lunch, do Summit, walk around, go into another place for dinner, etc...think of an outfit you can customize for cold outdoors and warm indoors. (In my case, I learned that my insulated hoodie fits easily in my backpack, but a leather jacket would not)

As a person who was born and still lives in Brooklyn NY. You are spot on to let people know about visiting NYC.
Weather in NY Changes very fast. From Hot and humid summers to Artic and Snowstorms in the winter. I have two apps on my phone 1 is the National Weather Service. 2 AccuWeather. I also watch a meteorologist who is on YouTube .
When it comes to the Subway. Always look for a striped bar on the platform. That is where the conductor is. Or go to the front of the platform. That is where the motorman is. They have radios to contact dispatchers who can call NYPD or FDNY or EMS..
When it comes to food such as bagels, pizza. I have no problem with other customers and workers.
NYC has lots of attractions especially during holiday season. Rangers, Knicks or a Concert at MSG. Rockefeller Center Christmas Tree üéÑ. Store windows. My favorite is Macy's. Dyker Heights in Brooklyn is excellent.
Summertime in Brooklyn is great. Coney Island has The Aquarium, Luna Park which includes the Cyclone. Denos which includes the Wonder Wheel, Nathan's and the Brooklyn Cyclones.
DUMBO is excellent. Brooklyn Bridge Park . Sheepshead Bay has restaurants, fishing boats and a Whale Watching boat.

Smart NY tourists watch your videos

Smart tourists:
Don‚Äôt take a cab or rideshare from one of the three area airports
Become familiar with adjacent subway lines that go in the same direction when the 1 they chosen inevitably gets delayed or rerouted
Do their clothing shopping in New Jersey because New Jersey doesn‚Äôt charge tax for clothes
Understand that the Manhattan grid that everyone is familiar with ceases to exist downtown, which features a lot more narrow and nonlinear streets, which can be confusing
That walking approximately 20 blocks north or south equals a mile if you walk parallel to the avenues
If you walk east to west, though walking perpendicular to the avenues, blocks are much longer
You will get outed as a tourist if you use any of these technical terms: Avenue of the Americas, Central Park South, and then there‚Äôs of course Houston Street‚Ä¶
Also, never underestimate the brutality of New York summers, heat, ridiculous humidity, and poorly air-conditioned/ventilated buildings‚Ä¶ You‚Äôve been warned
Understand that you will most likely not get to accomplish everything you want to accomplish on your visit, so it‚Äôs best just to select a few and take things at a bit more of a, slower, yet in depth pace

Also, I really like Tom Del Gato. He‚Äôs such a smart tour guide, focuses more in the history. However, if to put up with his humor, which‚Ä¶ Can be a little much

Coming in three weeks. Smart moves I made. Rather than stay in Manhattan. I booked a hotel in LIC. Easy walk to the subway, puts me in Times Square or Grand Central in 15 mins. Much cheaper rates and low crime levels. Booked early just before Covid restrictions were lifted. Saved a fortune.

Other smart moves, gave myself the last several months to work out a daily itinerary (if I don't stick to it exactly, that's fine, it's just a guide) worked out smart where to go and how to maximise time seeing and doing. So I am not back and forth all day missing out. Things I do are in a line basically. One after the other, smart and efficient. Little things like the best affordable breakfast places and so forth. Sure, I'll also just try pot luck but I'm doing my best to take the risk and disappointment out of the trip.

Used my time now to plan and find the deals and things I want to see and do, how to do it rather than wasting time when there. Every second is precious so I won't be wasting time unless it's enjoying the moment or just going off track to experience the city. Which is not wasting time at all! Scratching my head in my phone trying to work out where I am and what to do, that's wasting time. Not to mention making me a target.

I paid up front for a town car to pick me up at the airport and get me fast to the hotel. Again booked in advance so very reasonably priced. So I actually get a useful half day out of my travel day to NYC in the city.

Yes the subway or bus would have been cheaper but with a roller bag, shoulder bag and backpack, that's a hassle.

These counties have steadily lost population for the last 50 years and home prices are also losing ground and sitting vacant.  I had a long conversation with a local real estate executive and he explained that the state has abandoned these outlying counties forcing them to raise their taxes to unprecedented levels to survive. #1  Edited. Pack very  light. I, of course shower every day, and re-wear shirts-slacks/pants. On my first trip over 20 years ago, I brought a full size suitcase. Then I transitioned to a carry-on suitcase.   Now for a 3-day (my typical stay), I bring a good size backpack and a tote  bag.  The back pack is NOT a huge outdoor kitting backpack , but it's larger than the normal size.  I got it at Target.  Basically just a extra pair of lightweight Sketcher shoes (my storage space splurge), undies, minimal toiletries, small PJs.      The backpack is not heavy and saves me from pulling a wheeled bag from Penn Station to the hotel.      #2.  Learn the routes of where you're going on the subway before you get there.   I think I've gotten the letter and directions pretty well by now, but I am still struck with fear when I see "Express" because I don't know if they will go past my stops if I'm a little further out.   LOL. Otherwise though, it makes for a much better experience.    #3.  Definitely make a plan, if not excessively detailed.  I'm bad about frittering away my time, if I don't have a plan.   #4.  Make priority of what you want to visit.  The last couple of trips, I just ran out of steam, even with rest breaks.  I walk a lot, but at 20K steps, my legs just give out.  (And I walk a lot normally, just not used that that many steps in one day.  That's even with taking the subway, which includes a number of steps.)   #4.  If you come out of LaGuardia and don't have luggage -- and are not afraid of the subway, take the Q70-SBS bus to Roosevelt subway station.  I did that last December, and it was great.  #5.   You can put the OMNY on your credit card.  I did, and prefer it to having to grab and keep open my large-ish size iphone.

I worked in NYC most of my life.  I've pretty much seen it all on the subways.  I did fall for jumping into an 'empty' car once when the others were crowded.  Was a horrible ride to the next station with the smelliest homeless person ever.  haha As for danger, use common sense and the subways are usually quite safe.  Beware of pick pockets, don't flash cash or jewelry..stay back from the edge of the platform while waiting.  Stuff like that and stay with the crowds you will be fine.   As in nature, predators look for those that stray from the herd.  At tourist attractions, a lot of scammers work the crowds, and sometimes work in teams.  Again...don't take out your wallet...ususally best to simply say "no thanks".  Crowded tourist attractions always have police in or near the crowd sticking closer to them is a good idea.  Bad guys love to snatch gold chains, phones, purses from people.  Getting outright robbed is very rare, but that kind of stuff does happen when one wanders alone to that dark, lonely street.

If you do up in the wrong entrance, just take the next train in the wrong direction to a station that has a crossover and then grt on the right train. Ask anyone on the train where to do this, you will get help. It will probably be faster than waiting for the 18 minutes on an unlimited card. If you have a regular pay-per-ride card, it will save you the additional fare.

Those stations with separate entrances are, usually, local stops (as opposed to express stops) and one or two away, there will be an express stop that will have the crossover to the opposite direction.

New Yorkers are glad to help out-of-towners get around on the subway. We know it‚Äôs confusing. Ask politely and discover how hospitable New York really is.

Also, don‚Äôt buy or eat anything in Times Square. It‚Äôs bound to be a disappointment. For food go east (3rd avenue) or west (9th avenue) to find the places where natives eat.

Here's a simple solution to correcting getting on the wrong direction platform if you have the time and don't want to pay another $2.75:

Take the next train to an express or switch to another line stop -- those, by definition allow crossovers to the other direction to correct your mistake.

Occasionally there are local stops which allow crossovers, e.g. 1 line at 125th where you can change directions from within the stations.

Food carts:
Look for a Health Department inspection sticker. If it didn't get an "A" or doesn't have a sticker, keep walking.

Subway:
If you enter a station in the wrong direction, get on the train and ask another passenger (or the conductor) where you can change directions without paying an extra fare.


Driving:
DON'T. (From Manhattan, take a downtown B, D, N, Q train into Brooklyn for great views from the Manhattan Bridge, or take a #7 train to Queensboro Plaza for nice views of Midtown Manhattan.)

I really am a fan of the hop on hop off buses for first timers for several reasons. First, like you said, first day, you're tired, you don't have to do anything but sit. If you have little kids, it's a good move but mostly: it hits all the things that you went to see, but only need to look at. London is my city of choice and it's very walk-able but let's say you have little ones or limited stamina. You don't need to do anything at Houses of Parliament and Elizabeth tower but look at it. You don't need to do anything at Monument but look at it. Tower bridge, you're most likely just wanting to look at it. Even the London Eye, you may want to ride it but to get the iconic pictures, you can get them from the bus. Hyde Park, Piccadilly, Trafalgar - yes they have things to do but you get to look at it. After that day, you have got your photo ops and seen where everything is THEN you do your footwork.

Storytime-

So I gave a guy $10 for his ‚Äòmixtape‚Äô Cd back like 15or so yrs ago.
He said he was only expecting $5.
I told him, I was investing towards his future as he wouldn‚Äôt dare hand out Music which he didn‚Äôt put his heart and soul into (yea, I know‚Ä¶I was a bit naive to the Venice street ways back then)üòÇ. Worse is, I truly believed what I was saying, as I hadn‚Äôt paid attention to this being a common scheme down there. Especially given nobody had ever approached me selling their CDs at that point, so the situation couldn‚Äôt have worked out an better than it had- thanks to the Lord I‚Äôm sure.

Anyhow, he stared at me for a few seconds before he hugged me and began crying saying he had never thought of the money being given in that aspect.
Thats how little he thought of himself at that time- just trying to make a Buck around there as all of the rest of them were doing.
I told him I go around and drop a dollar into all of the street perform collection hats, whether I saw their show or not.
But for him? I invested.
I did tell him, prior to even knowing what type of music was on the cd (if anything) I did expect him to develop a solid plan for his future since he *seemed like a promising man for some reason.
While he was probably in his beg. to mid 30‚Äôs, nobody had ever asked him what his dreams were, nor did he ever consider them to be able to come true.
I said he was already ahead of the game since he took the initiative to at least get his music out there, along with the time and effort in making it all happen. And how I respected those whom actually ‚Äòworked‚Äô instead of those who just stood around begging.
Anyway, it was years ago and I always wondered what happened to him.

Turns out, when we got to car my boys anxiously popped the cd in, as we all guessed what genre of music it‚Äôd be. The guy was dressed in typical ‚Äòrapper‚Äô wear (as I was used to in LA at least), so we figured it was some type of rap.
Turned out to be a freakin SWEET R&B cd!
Like, idk how he produced it, but we were blown away.
Then as we had people in our car and we played it, they‚Äôd all want to borrow it too! I don‚Äôt remember now what their band name was or any of them actually, but we did try to find him online, but it was right when fb was just starting out, and couldn‚Äôt find anything by his name- or even if it was a stage name.
That‚Äôs too bad cuz it was an entire cd full of awesome music.
And then a kid must‚Äôve jacked the cd at some point cuz it just sorta disappeared from our car.üôÅ
Only later when I was telling the story, did I learn about people selling their CDs on the street and it was a legit thing!

Here's another tip: When strolling on the sidewalk, if you want to pause to take a photo, step close to the curb (but obviously not into traffic) or back against the side of a building to take your photo.
NEVER stop right in the middle of the sidewalk because you will impede the flow of pedestrian traffic and are likely to get shouldered or bumped into by a fast-moving pedestrian.

Here are a couple more (you may have covered some in other videos - so watch the NYC Tips Playlist). 1a Not factoring in the location of where you're staying in relation to where the majority of places you plan to visit are located. 1b Planning to "Uber it everywhere" or not planning your transportation in advance - traffic and surge pricing will eat into your time and cost savings. 2. Dressing for fashion over function - unless you're going to a gala at the Met or a restaurant that requires a dinner jacket, keep it basic and functional. 3. Not bringing a reusable poncho and a quality drawstring backpack. The drawstring backpack is easy to pack, not as bulky, and good for carrying your water bottle, poncho, etc.

Tip: If you do have a car (perhaps you're on a road trip and NYC is one of your stops) park at a train station in the suburbs and take the train into the city. It will be cheaper by the time you factor in tolls, parking, and possible tickets. Plus the time it will take you to drive in and out of the city is about the same time or more compared to taking the train from the suburbs.
Another major mistake that should be added is visiting the same chain eateries in NYC that one can find in one's own home town.

Actually avoided a lot of these by watching a ton of your videos and piecing the tips together.  Great compilation video.  If I can add a tip, consider a bicycle tour of Central Park.  Rent an e-bike if you worry about hills or pedaling for a couple hours.  We saw most of the major attractions and can now target specific areas to focus on in future visits.

I definitely concur with the "knowing what you plan to order before getting online" tip. Once when I was a teen, we came into the city and stopped off at a diner for lunch. When I started hemming and hawing about what to order, the server straight up told me "I ain't got time for you, boy!"" Kind of sums it up.

I lived in NYC for years and tip#4 is gold. New yorkers really aren't rude, but if you stop and look for directions in a busy part of a station or in the middle of the sidewalk you'll get some crap. As a tourist please be aware that 9 million people actually live here and they're trying to get to work/pick up kids/buy groceries/get home.

My two big tips: 1) spend time in the outer boroughs. They're less busy but there's lots of great things to see like Coney Island, Arthur Avenue, Brooklyn museum, etc. 2) schedule a Big Apple Greeter. Did you know you can get a free tour guide to take you around for 4 hours? They even match you with someone with similar interests as you.

I am visiting New York City  in mid March and your videos are extremely helpful - thanks. For what it is worth, I remember hearing my parents and their friends talking about visiting NYC in the sixties and their comment about cabbies was that it was always best to give the driver an intersection rather than an actual address.

One of the biggest mistakes I made as a tourist in NYC was telling the taxi driver I wasn‚Äôt from NYC and was in fact a tourist. At first, he came off as very friendly and polite, but that quickly changed once the ride was over. I didn‚Äôt have cash on me, so when I went to pay with my card, I clicked the card paying option and all of the sudden he was demanding I pay in cash and that I had apparently clicked the cash paying option, which I certainly did not. My sister was there as a witness. After arguing with me for a few minutes, he forced me take out money from an ATM at a nearby convenience store after threatening to call the police. Moral of the story is: always carry cash on you when riding a taxi and don‚Äôt let them know you‚Äôre a tourist. I ended up taking Lyfts and Ubers the rest of the trip when I wasn‚Äôt walking. üòÖ
Thank you for your and Ben's honesty! Thanks for also sharing challenges tourists and others can make while in NYC.

About issue n¬∞4, my idea would be to plan every one of your commutal travels (metro, bus) before your trip, and then at each night in your hotel or B&B or whatever dorm location you are, double check your tomorrow trip and see if there's no station or bus stop that's closed for some reason.
Great tips John and things that everyone, not just tourists must follow. Must admit they're pretty much tips for absolutely anywhere in the world regardless of how big or small the city.

As a Londoner who visited New York (just Yesterday as of from this post) I do have to say the city is AMAZING üòç I am glad to say that I only did 2 of the things that you said to avoid to 1 of which is Central Park we spent 2 hrs in Central Park but we did want to do other things 2 was misreading the Subway but I must say that is probably the only gripe I've got with NY. The public transport either partial informal or just isn't informal non whatsoever (tho I never did use the bus so I cannot speak for that) but go to any London Underground & you will know not just your line (or be reassured that this line will call at your stop) but also if there are any lines ideal for you to transfer in order to reach your destination. Not only that but I wish that for the sake tourist's there was any way to say if this is a stop that is nearby a landmark for example if you were at London Underground & you wanted to get off at Hyde Park or Buckingham Palace the train via an automated PA or on map will say "this is Green Park alight here for Hyde Park or Buckingham Palace " other than that the Subway was ok to use but one I can't stand is NTransit (NJ Transit?ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è) but you really need to be more forthcoming with the info on your trains dude we only used it twice (from & to the airport) but using your train system was hella confusing. Thank you for pointing out that New Yorkers are almost always willing to help out visitors. We're usually in a hurry (I mean, just look at the place!) but if your question is specific you'll get a quality answer most of the time. If you're ever in a real jam, there's no one you'd rather have around than a New Yorker!

I was in NYC last September and avoided the Observation decks because I did not want to get into long lines. I almost did get the train in the wrong direction once and this seems to be more common on the tiny stations with old confusing signage.

I know people assume that New Yorkers are jerks, but we were just there for the first time for a week in April, and every single local we interacted with was *wonderful*. Friendly, helpful, engaging. We didn‚Äôt have a single bad experience, and we‚Äôre from the south, so we have a pretty high standard for friendliness üòÖ

That weather report tip, to me, is mostly common sense but even so, you should do it everywhere, including your hometown, not just NYC.  And the stopping at the topping at the top of the stairs is simply common courtesy and can be applied to many other places ie the escalator at the mall amd is something you should have learned in early childhood.

Another subway tip: Check the status of the subway line you plan on using ahead of time. When I visited NYC back in September, I flew into JFK and took the E train to Midtown. I was supposed to get off at Port Authority, which was the closest station to my hotel, but that morning the E train was rerouted onto the F line at Bryant Park. Not a big deal, but it was the first time I ever rode the NYC subway, so it did catch me off guard at first.

Later that same day, I was trying to take the F train uptown from 23rd Street to Rockefeller Center, but they had the entrance taped off at the station. Checked the Metro App. 14th and 23rd Uptown stops on the F Line were closed for the evening. I'm guessing for maintenance? Anyways, I had to take the F Train downtown to 4th Street just so I could get on the Uptown train. As a first time visitor to NYC, it was a learning experience and I nearly missed my scheduled appointment at Top of the Rock because of it.

Great video!  Also, be careful with those 'cage-like' revolving subway entrances. If you don't enter the very first opening available, it'll steal your fare & lock you out. Grab any luggage or packages thru the emergency exit once you've payed & entered.

Some mistakes I've made when I went to New York:

- Bought a chicken kabob at a food cart near Times Square for a whopping $8. It was terrible. A Sabrett hot dog was $4 near Penn Station and it was okay for NYC street food
- Hopping on the wrong subway train and being on the wrong side of the subway station (it happens)
- Spent a good chunk of money on a MetroCard that never worked. If you have a contactless card on you, you'd be fine with just that.
- Leave lots of time for museums. There's a lot more to see than what you think.
- Don't eat too much since you can't enjoy other great food too

You have to be careful about booking a hotel there.
You might try going through a travel agent. It either costs nothing or a modest fee. But I believe you can avoid off the wall hotels.
It's not required by the hotel to inform potential guests that the hotel houses homeless.
Before you book with a hotel, look up on the internet for a rating, that might explain it. And you can even call the hotel or email them asking if they rent to homeless.
20% of hotels in NYC rent to homeless.
If you go there, try to look like a New Yorker and not a tourist. When someone comes up to you and wants to start a conversation, get away from the person.
It could be anywhere from a pick pocket to a scammer. That rule should be applied most other tourist destinations as well.
You can see an aircraft carrier there and go inside it as well as a sub.
When you go on the subway stay away the platform near the tracks, just to stay on the safe side. Insane people have pushed people onto the tracks.

If you visit NY and plan to drive there, do some research and find a parking lot for the time you will be in town.  Leave the car parked in a lot in Queens or in a safe neighborhood where it's free. Do not drive into Manhattan. Use public transportation. Not only will a subway get you to your destination faster and without a hassle, you will also not waste your vacation time looking for parking or paying through the nose for s spot or risking at least a $100 fine.

Oh and one other tip. It is still a functioning city with lots of people trying to get to where they need to go. Lots of people are in a hurry so if you do, think, act, or behave in any way that is going to inconvenience or delay anyone else you'll stick out like a sore thumb, and you'll be a jerk. Everyone gets lost, even NYers, so if you do get out of the way. Everyone needs to double check their phone or directions or their food order or whatever, just get out of the way when you do. Everyone sometimes makes mistakes on the train. Laugh it off and switch to the right one or the right direction and keep going. Also, don't be afraid to ask MTA people about the subway. It can be pretty confusing esp if you're dead tired from jet lag like I was and couldn't for the life of me figure out my butt from a hole in the ground, but eventually you'll make it fine. It's not Tokyo's subway in terms of comfort, efficiency, and figuring out where to go, but it helps.

Getting a taxi can also be annoying, and there are a few unspoken rules about it, so yes I know the taxi drivers need the money but to be honest Lyft or Uber was the best option for some of the things I had to do. Just be clear of where you are on the street and who to look out for, and don't wait on the side of a bus lane where they can't park if you can help it.

Make reservations as much as you can for your food. You'll be glad you did because the better places fill up quickly. You'll be doing a lot of walking and will not want to wait for your food.

As far as pizza goes, yes everyone goes to Joes, but branch out if you can. Everyone has a little different taste, and like Tokyo where you can survive off of 24 hour ramen, if you find a great pizza place that sells by the slice in NYC close to your stay that's open late, you're set. If you want Joe's? Be prepared to wait 30 min for a few slices at least. OR you can have it delivered. A whole pie with tip delivered can run you $40 but its large enough that you'll have it in your fridge for days.

I also think the WTC is the best observation tower in the city. Better than Vanderbilt and the Empire state building. Empire is way too crowded (but if you want to see it once, go ahead). One Vanderbilt was fairly crowded but really was too much of a gimmick to be worth the price they were charging. Plus the WTC is a lot faster getting to the views.

So the car thing needs to be expanded upon. THERE IS NO STREET PARKING IN Manhattan, or, at least, that's how you should treat it. I may have found on-street parking once in all my years of driving into NYC. And, FYI, the parking garages are insanely expensive (bank on at least $100 a night), and, very often, if you don't get there early enough, they'll fill up. There are also ZERO gas stations in Manhattan, the traffic is perpetually brutal, roadwork is everywhere and non-stop, and the cabbies are insane . Couple all that with the fact that NYC is probably the one place in all of North America where the mass transit is genuinely convenient and easy on-and-off, and you get to a point where the conclusion is a very straight-forward

This video fully introduced New York City through its history, current condition, and the filmer's personal experience of visiting this city. New York City is so magnetic that almost every ambitious person wants to be here. This megacity has the most job opportunities for employees to succeed around the globe, even though it is typically tough to afford the living costs in the beginning days. Moreover, New York City is the most diverse and inclusive metropolis compared to other cities, which is due to the roughly 800 languages spoken here and the well-developed ethnic communities. So if you want to make your dream come true as far as possible, just pick your luggage and dive into this city!

I used to go to New York for work and really miss going there. NYC has everything, Broadway shows, great restaurants, museums, everything you might look for in a large city. And there is a certain "buzz" to New York when you are walking around, not to mention all of the history as well.

So I stayed two more years while I researched where else I might to live. I moved to a western state with I live in the Old Town section of a moderate city -- I can still walk to everything I need like my life in Manhattan but this particular city is SO clean with no litter and no graffiti, beautiful murals and large floral displays in season.
One thing I miss though is the diversity of Manhattan -- SO glad I lived there most of my life -- Manhattan exceeded my expectations!

Not a bad review, but the video should be at least 1 1/2 hours long to really see all the sights. Also, shooting the video on a bright clear day in 4K would be great.In this way, you can really see the beauty ( and filth) of the city. There's Battery Park, South Street Seaport, 34th Street with Macy's and tons of other shops, seeing Times Square at night with all the lighted billboards, people ( and freaks) in Manhattan, Prospect Park in Brooklyn, a nice sunny day ride on the Staten Island Ferry where you can see the gorgeous downtown skyline, The Bronx Zoo, the miles long strip of beaches in Queens in the Rockaways. One thing about New York City, there is likely no cuisine from around the world you can't find or run out of things to do. It can be filthy in some places in every borough, but it's not all people make it out to be.

My recommended rule of thumb after living in NYC for more than a decade is to never give to anyone who solicits on the street ANYTHING no matter their story or 'service.' You could apply this rule of thumb ANYWHERE outside of NYC too. You're not participating in tourism when you give those folks money. Those folks were just whiny losers and hustlers, not artists or established tourism businesses. Literally everyone in this video was a nobody who asked for money for pictures or nothing. The Naked Cowboy seems to be the only exception. It appeared he doesn't actually solicit money but rather displays and makes money from his other products. I noticed he didn't solicit anything in this interview. Ever meet a REAL celebrity and taken a photo? Do they ever ask for money? Wouldn't you rather go to NYC and get in a photo with a movie star for free rather than some lying loser hustler who asks for 5, 10, 20 dollars?

Also never accept anything for free unless it's in the name of public service like a face mask during COVID. For instance, those CD guys in Time Square will tell you to take it without charge like it's a free sample then turn around on you demanding money, not accept the CD back, pull the race card, act like a victim and accuse you of not paying. Anyone actually about the art either does it for free or doesn't solicit from others.

Love this! My memories of living and visiting NYC over the years are precious and many! Standing on a long, long line in the freezing cold waiting to go into Radio City Music Hall when I was a kid, looking at all the magnificent store windows at Christmas time esp. the famous magical Lord & Taylor ones which we took our three daughters to see as well, the Tree at Rockefeller Center and when I was really little eating hot chestnuts from a brown paper bag on the steps of the gorgeous NY Public Library at night with those wreaths around the necks of those stone Lions at the front of the library! When I lived in Manhattan, shopping at all the stores at Xmas and having to walks blocks against the freezing wind to my apartment on the Upper East Side! The wind would come blasting down those streets from the East River! The Christmas decorations everywhere! Going to see the Nutcracker Suite at Lincoln Center and then the snow coming down when we got out! There was also a wonderful little German candy store on East 86th Street that sold novelty chocolates and gingerbread houses because Yorkville used to be heavily populated with people of German descent like myself on my paternal side. When you live in NYC or visit there, you soak up as many wonderful memories as you can! Had a couple of negative experiences like being robbed once which was terrifying, but other than that, it's mostly positive ones, thankfully! A fun exciting city and remember sensing the electricity in the air once when I was staying at a friend's apt which looked right out on the top of the Empire State Building all lit up at night! AMAZING! "New York, New York, it's a wonderful town, the Bronx is up and the Battery's down" like the song goes from the 1940s along with some other wonderful songs that the late great Frank Sinatra sang about New York City! Thanks so much for sharing...wonderful job! Merry Christmas, Happy Holidays, Happy Chanukah and a Happy New Year to all! New Years in NYC is also a REAL BLAST!
