We just came back from NYC - about a week ago. I love your videos along with Brett's and Sarah's. I watch them all the time and I thought I knew what I was doing, but the moment we landed in NYC, everything become very chaotic... Our younger son got sick and from there on, everything was just walking around the city. We went to Central Park starting from the Zoo and we could only get to the Lake. Everything is so distracting that we did not have much more time to see anything else. What I think will be a great idea and I will definitely do it next time - Print a map of the park with markings for all the attractions from this video, for example. Then you won't miss anything by just passing near it and not noticing. I have created a channel (https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCfATbNCbCD-jKXjNBSgEkvg) with all the videos we did in NYC, but I have not uploaded those from Central Park yet. There was a man singing "Pretty Woman" very very good, there was another one that was collecting foreign currency and got very excited when we told him we are from Bulgaria. Then our 3 yo kid decided to feed the ducks with pretzels LOL. So from conversation to conversation and we could not see even 1/4 of the Park. Having a visible map in front of your face while you walk can be great. The phone will not always work, because in the middle of the day you will be trying to preserve your battery for photos or just to be able to call an Uber to your hotel. Another cool thing about the paper map is that you can print the walking distance to each spot. We found this the hard way. I went for pizza one evening after I saw that the place is just around the corner only two blocks away on the same street. I ended up walking 2km to that place and with the order, it took me between 30 to 60 minutes to return with the Pizza

15 and counting! Great ideas in your video: a few more: ¬†
-- The beautiful bridges -- especially the Bow Bridge for the most beautiful views in the park over the lakes often filled with several couples rowing and the grand apartments of Central Park West, including the Dakota peering over the treetops.
-- The Rambles which feels like a true forest that you can even get lost in, with hilly trails and beautiful views at every twist and turn.
-- Seeing concerts of the NY Philharmonic on the Great Lawn, with 10s of thousands of people on the lawn with picnic baskets and bottles of wine soaking in the most beautiful music as the twilight sky becomes darker and darker and where you can actually see the stars right in the beating heart of NYC.
-- Having lunch or dinner at the Boathouse Cafe or at Tavern on the Green, with their sublime settings, and quite good food.
-- Taking in the breathtaking views from "The Pond", a smaller lake in the Southeast Corner of the park, framed by towering trees and the beautiful buildings of Central Park South gracefully rising above the tree tops and with the new soaring skyscrapers rising above those.
-- Watching genuinely spectacular roller skaters just south of the overlook of Bethesda Fountain.
-- The broad walkway along the east side of Sheep Meadow, with towering old trees lining the walkway.
- Without Central Park, NYC would .be a different city entirely. It serves as the "back yard" for millions of people. Its the beating heart of the city -- its lush green Center, its very heart and soul.

They do it every summer in Central Park and it's completely free (just you might have to wait in line, which for a free show, isn't that bad). They have three shows happening this summer, first is Much Ado About Nothing, next is Coriolanus, and finally is Disney's Hercules, which I am totally going to see. Barr in one of his videos gave one of the wisest pieces of advice which was not to do too much on your first day in New York. However, with the madness of wanting to see more and more, I didn't and on the first day, after riding the bus that took me to know the lower part of manhattan, I decided to go from times square walk all the uper west side to the cathedral of saint john divine to do the vertical tour , go up the tower and then go down the whole of central park. I really did that but and there is always but not everything went smoothly. First I got there at two and didn't even take the tour because I thought there might not be enough time to see all of central park and I'd have to wait until 3. Then I went through central park to bevery castle. Well, I thought it was beautiful and walked and walked but always happy. Turns out I had a ticket bought online to see the met. I thought that's easy I'm close but I got on the Rambles and ended up in the opposite place... I went straight to the Dakota building which was cool because I wanted to see it but being there I went down and went to the columbus circle hotel plaza and went up all the way again to to the MET museum. On the way I was already a zombie but a happy zombie. When I got there I still saw the Egyptian part and two more floors, until I practically couldn't walk normally. It looked like the skeetch of the mont pyhntons from the weird floor department. To go down the stairs I had to support myself. Upon leaving, I took a taxi and went to the hotel, which was not far away on 40 street, right next to the bus station. Conclusion, in theory I went all over central park but in practice I didn't see half of what they say in the video. That is, no matter how hard you try, it's huge and you can't see everything in the same day. The next day I was back to normal but I realized that New York was just like that and that when I felt that I was already exhausted it was better to stop and enjoy things calmly, besides I was traveling solo and despite being super safe it was convenient to be 100% . So I did that, I walked so much that I didn't even use the subway, I went from Times Square to Wall Street and a little further and from the Manhattan Bridge to Times Square, times square almost to harlem ... but when I saw that i was in a mess, I rested and sometimes i it was 4 o clock in the afertnoon  and i was resting in the hotel but its was necessary ! I loved this city , really amazing!

The Central Park Zoo, The Delacorte Theater (Shakespeare in the Park), right above the the carousel...chess tables, near the Sheep Meadow (They stopped putting sheep out there because people were stealing them for food during the Great Depression), The Ramble, sand "beach" volleyball (just east of the Sheep Meadow and South of Summer Stage theater.) Horse Bridle paths and stables...some people...$$$...actually put their horses up in the stables and come to the Park to ride them...crazy money there. Tavern on the Green restaurant and bar AND the best public restrooms in the Park....just west of the Sheep Meadow. They play baseball on the fields to the north (The Great Lawn) and softball to the South. I used to work at the Park Lane Hotel on Central Park South (59th Street) and play softball in the Hotel league on Saturday mornings. {{You generally need a permit to actually play on those fields}} There a several "Leagues", Broadway, Hotels, Advertising, TV Networks...all with permits for different days and times....you may see a Broadway Star playing with the rest of their cast/crew sometimes.

If you play Pokemon Go, you can run into many landmarks and stumble onto many areas of the park as you hunt for monsters with your phone. The game conveniently makes landmarks and certain locations as Poke Stops which not only goads the player to journey further within the park but helps the player discover more Pokemon along the way.

I think you forgot the balto statue. Great spot to see history and honor the dog that started the Iditarod race. Balto was the lead dog of the sled team that helped bring medicine to cure a Diphtheria outbreak. The medicine was transferred from sled to sled but only balto‚Äôs team ran 3/4 of the way while the other sleds either crashed or got stuck in a monster blizzard. It made him an instant hero saving thousands of lives mostly children. The dog lived the rest of days in a zoo well cared for and his remains were stuffed and put in a museum while NYC honor the dog with the statue. I do know some of kids from the outbreak live in New York and their descendants too. They go at least once a year to give thanks.

TLDR - Top 15 Things to do in Central Park, New York City

1. Wander‚Ä¶ with no plan (Central Park)
2. Ride the Central Park Carousel (Southern Park near East 65th)
3. Stay active at Sheep Meadow (66th to 60tth st next to Central Park Mall)
4. Visit Strawberry Fields (Westside between 71st and 74th)
5. See the Minton Tiles at Bethesda Terrace Arcade 9Mid Park at 72nd St, front of Central Park Lake)
6. Alive in Wonderland Statue (Enter 76th and 5th walk down ramp to right of lake)
7. Sail model boats in the park (Enter 76th and 5th, walk to water down ramp to left)
8. Talk to the Whisper Bench (inside Shakespeare Garden Westside Park be. 79th and 80th)
9. Find Cleopatra‚Äôs Needle (behind Metropolitan Museum of Art in park)
10. Admire the view from the Met‚Äôs rooftop (5th floor Metropolitan Museum 82nd and 5th) *Pay to enter
11. Find the Loch (Mid Park 105th in the Ravine 100 ft from Huddlestone Arch)
12. Take photos at Huddlestone Arch (Mid Park 10th in the Ravine)
13. Explore the Conservatory Garden (enter near 5th ave and 10th st)
14. Go fishing at Harlem Meer (Charles A. Dana Discovery Center inside Central Park at 110th St between 5th and Lenox Ave)
15. See history at the Blockhouse (Westside 108th and Adam Clayton Powell Jr Blvd. (North Woods)

comment: I was blessed to be able to visit NYC on business back when that was a thing. I had to work about 4 hours over 2 afternoons. I was there at the SoHo Grand Hotel for 5 days! I had a blast! Empire State Building at night is incredible. Visited Lady Liberty, Wall Street, the World Trade Center Twin Towers (alas, I didn‚Äôt go in, just put my hand on the South Tower and looked up), NY Public Library, Central Park, Times Square, Greenwich Village (Two Boots Pizza!), Gramercy Park, Broadway, rode the subway, hailed a cab, ate a hot dog on the street, and sat in on the filming of a music interview with Jazz guitarist, Lee Ritenour. I gave my company-supplied ticket to Rent to my coworker so she could take her boyfriend and I spent my time wandering the city looking at places notable to fans of Lawrence Block‚Äôs Matt Scudder novels (A Walk Among the Tombstones, etc). Five days, alone and unencumbered, STILL wasn‚Äôt enough to even begin to scratch the surface of this amazing and beautiful city! I will definitely be back.

I remember that, during my childhood, if I wanted to visit other places of the world, I had three options: or to scan through TV channels looking for documentaries about somewhere outside my country - in which case I couldn't choose what to see, I would have to try my best to enjoy the experience, or I stared at the pictures in that year's Barsa's Yearbook, or I had to look at the "hi-def" photos from my dad's Viewmaster that came on disks, and the way you used that is you chose a disk, like the Japan disk, plop it into the Viewmaster's binoculars and by pushing a lever at the side of the thingamabob you would advance one photo at a time.

I could barely imagine how awesome and immersive the options we have nowadays are, to the point where, if you concentrate enough, you almost feel like you're walking at the place.

If I had seen anything like this video during my childhood, this experience would have blown my mind in so many levels that it's hard to imagine how would I feel about it.

I was born in Cincinnati, Ohio and lived here all of my life, 66 years. I have been to NYC 2 times for several days each and LOVED every minute, even when they towed my car while staying at the Hyatt (52nd street?). Turns out it was not Hyatt parking, my fault. My brother was a block from the WTC on 9/11. Someone pounding on the window was screaming to get out and run so he did. He ran to Battery park and hid behind a tree to avoid the giant dust cloud from the 1st building rushing across the bottom of the island. Even after all of that, I still yearn to go back. Your video shows so many familiar places and so much more that we missed. It is to much to see in less than a week (Maybe a month?). Winter was HELL but still awesome. Spring and fall are picture perfect. Some friends told me once, "You don't want to go there. The people are so rude." Let me tell you, that is NOT true. Having gone to Florida more than once, we thought they were sooo slow... This is why many people don't like New York City. People do not understand that the fast of living in NYC does not allow you to think about what you want. Waiters will walk away. Figure out what you want, then signal them and they will come back. If you are from a big city, like Chicago? The people will seem normal. I guess we seem like hicks to them.

Hi Erik, I'm spanish speaker and here's the subtitles of your video for students who are learning english:
No matter how many times you have been at to New York. The city can always overwhelm you with a crazy amount of things to experience. yeah so I've already covered what not to do in New York in a previous video and I've teamed up with Google who's sponsoring today's video. Using the Chromebook to take on the challenge of sharing with you my comprehensive expert list of what TO DO in New York City! Number one on my list is...

Free movie night in Bryant Park
Bryant park is located here on West 41st St and 6th avenue right next to Time Square. Every Monday during the summer, starting in about June through late August, a movie plays under the bright lights of the city in Bryant Park. There‚Äôs this nostalgic atmosphere here and people from all over the city and the world is coming out to enjoy an old-fashioned film in the middle of the city for free. The lawn opens up at 5 p.m. and at the website advises you to arrive early, which you should 100% do if you want to get a spot on the lawn. It fills up fast and it's a first-come-first-serve basis. If you're hungry there are food vendors on the fountain terrace with tons of meal options, all this information can be found on the Bryant Park website along with a list of the films playing for the entire summer. There is nothing like seeing a film on the big screen with New York City as your backdrop.

Support Local Restaurants
Now this is a bold claim but I truly believe that the number one way to find anything while traveling in 2018 is by Instagram. When I arrive in a new city I go on Instagram and check out the location tag of specific places around the city I want to explore. I browse through the top photos to gain some inspiration or ideas on places to see and of course places to eat. When in New York you want to eat at local establishments, you know places with character. This is one of my go-to coffee spots in the city right by Washington Square Park. It was opened in 1927 and the Italian cappuccino was actually introduced to America by the founder of this Cafe. Almost a century later and it still has that old school New York Jazz vibe. The perfect place to come in early, get some work done and of course had the original cappuccino. Basically anywhere that is not a chain restaurant is the way to go.

Rent a bike
So I'm a bit biased but my favorite way to see the any new city is by bike and New York is no exception, now if you don't own a bike that's no problem. There is Rideshare bike stations on almost every block in New York. Now the streets in New York are hectic even with the designated by claims, that's why I recommend heading over to the West Side Highway bike path. It runs the whole west side of Manhattan along the Hudson River, you can bike or run here without having to worry about traffic. There is also some the best views in entire city over here at Pier 63 and the next activity on my list which is a boat tour around Manhattan. .

Sunset boat tour
By far, one of the best ways to see unparalleled views of Manhattan is from the water on the Hudson River. You have a few options for ways to get out on the water. You can pay the $30 for a New York waterways site tour, for the thrill seeker and a bit more money you can rent some jet skis, then there's the Staten Island Ferry for $4.86, you can rent or book a sailboat tour or you can round up some friends and throw a party on a yacht.

I recommend going at Golden hour you know right around Sunset with those views it is the perfect Instagram shot. You can even pop your photos right in the lightroom on the boat and edit and post in real time.

The boat that I took left from Chelsea Piers, we made our way down to the Statue of Liberty and I'm talkin right up close to Lady Liberty with Incredible views of One World Trade Center and Lower Manhattan. Right as those city lights start to sparkle, then we made our way back up the river with iconic shots of the Empire State Building and the midtown skyline. If you want those views I highly recommend a boat tour but if you're into boat rides that are let's just say a bit more laid back then I recommend heading up to Central Park to the paddle boats.

Central park row boats
Now, Central Park is massive. It was established in 1857. My pro tip is to drop a pin on Google Maps at locations in the part that you want to revisit just because it is so massive and it's easy to get lost.

This is definitely one of the more romantic things to do in the city. Now you can rent a boat from 10 a.m. until about sundown. For my biggest piece of advice is get here early as the day goes on this place gets packed. It's a cash-only operation, it costs $15 per hour with a $20 cash deposit.

You can hear some soft jazz often a distance, beautiful summer day, this is one of my favorite things to do that I actually don't do enough. There is nothing more unique than being in the middle of the city on the lake with no people around, I mean just look at this view, come here to decompress, to dish stress from the hectic hustle and bustle of midtown, enjoy some fresh air surrounded by nature and of course, hear some incredible live jazz music.

Off-off Broadway show
So don‚Äôt get wrong, Broadway shows are absolutely amazing. I love ‚ÄúWicked‚Äù just as much as ‚ÄúThe next guy‚Äù but my pro tip is get off Broadway and see some of off off Broadway plays in the city. Fun fact, when I first moved to the city I actually had an internship at the actor studio in Hell's Kitchen so you know, there‚Äôs tons a lot of theaters all around the city.

Off off Broadway shows are less expensive, a cozy intimate environment and many times more entertaining and authentic than a big-budget show. If you‚Äôre unsure what show to see off Broadway you can always check to see what shows are selling discounted tickets through the tickets app. And as an alternative to check near play, go to a stand-up comedy show at one of my favorite spots in the whole city is the Gotham Comedy Club, there's nothing like seeing a live show in the city.

The Manhattanhenge
It‚Äôs safe to say that the most photogenic days are during the summer in NYC. Four times a year, the sun aligns perfectly with Manhattan's East West grid creating the Manhattanhenge coined by Neil deGrasse Tyson as an ode to Stonehenge.

The reason that the Manhattanhenge is so rare is the fact that you have to have perfectly clear skies on a night like tonight, to get the sun to set right down there in between the streets of Manhattan. The best places to view the Manhattanhenge are on 14th, 23th, 42nd, and 57th street.

Two hundreds years ago, the architects who created the plan for modern Manhattan decided to use a grid system with avenues that run north to south and streets east to west and that choice set the stage before the Manhattanhenge to occur.

As for the Staten Island Ferry, lately a lot of people have been coming in to Staten Island and then just turning around and leaving because this borough did a VERY POOR JOB of advertising what it's got. Great video. Just a few notes from a native

1) the Sim Cards in the airport are knockoff garbage. If you buy one and it doesn't work you will not get a refund

2) you can use the same MetroCard on the AirTrain and Subway as long as it's a Pay-per-ride card and not unlimited. You'll actually get a free transfer from Air Train to Subway as it'll detect the swipe in your card. Thus you would only pay the 7.75 total

3) if you are visiting anywhere near mid-town it's going to be a lot faster to take the LIRR, even if it's Times Square. Right as you exit the LIRR you can immediately transfer for the subway or walk. The subway will take you a lot longer

4) UBER does not have a special NYC rate. They will charge you around $30-$40 to go from JFK to Manhattan. (The hustlers will charge you upwards of $100 but that's a whole other story)

Overall though, your video was great and informative

A few notes about this from a Native New Yorker who lives in Queens, not too far from the LIRR in Jamaica. The LIRR is nicer, more upscale than the Subway, butg obvkiously more expensive. The LIRR Cars also have bathrooms (NO Showers) but Toilets, maybe not the Cleanest which NYC Subway Cars don't have. I think during the Pandemic they got rid of the BAthrooms in NYC Subway Staions which defintely were not the NIcest.
If you take the Subway form Jaimaica since it is one of the first Stops, you should be able to get a Seat on the E Train. Another option maybe Renata will cover this later is to take the Q60 Bus near the LIRR Jamaica Terminal which ends go along Queens Blvd and end up stopping in Manhattan as the last stop by the 59th Street Bridge really 60th Street and 2nde Avenue. The Q60 would be a long ride during the day especially Rush Hour into Manhattan- defintely over a hour, more like 90 MInutes, shorter at Night. The Q60 Bus takes the Metro CArd like the Subways and I believe the New Omni Card MTA is beginning to use to repalce the Metro Card. I am old fashioned and prefer the Metro Card.
I beleive one can take other MTA Buses like the Q10 to go to and from JFK as well which should requre a regular MTA FAre unlike the AirTrain which now I see is $7.75 as opposed to the Bus which is $2.75 and you get one free transfer either to the Subway or another bus as long as you use it within 3 hours (I think the transfer period was 2 hours when this first began a number of years ago, but I heard it is 3 hours now)

You only have to pay for the AirTrain at Jamaica and Howard Beach. Every other stop is free, and some buses stop at the free AirTrain stations.

So you can get to Penn Station for just the $2.75 by taking the AirTrain to Lefferts Blvd, then taking the Q10 Limited to the final stop (Kew Gardens E station), then using the free transfer to take the E train to Penn Station. The train station is 1 block away from the Q10 bus stop, and I believe it's also accessible.

Hope that helps, and enjoy a pizza pie with the $15+ you saved between you and your husband!
